1
00:01:33,280 --> 00:01:37,273
<i>My father's name was John Kinsella.</i>
<i>It's an Irish name.</i>

2
00:01:37,840 --> 00:01:40,035
<i>He was born in North Dakota in 1896...</i>

3
00:01:40,120 --> 00:01:41,633
<i>...and never saw a big city...</i>

4
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:44,871
<i>...until he came back from France in 1918.</i>

5
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:49,234
<i>He settled in Chicago, where he learned</i>
<i>to live and die with the White Sox.</i>

6
00:01:49,680 --> 00:01:52,513
<i>Died a little</i>
<i>when they lost the 1919 World Series...</i>

7
00:01:53,160 --> 00:01:55,833
<i>...died a lot the following summer</i>
<i>when eight teammates...</i>

8
00:01:55,920 --> 00:01:58,115
<i>...were accused of throwing that Series.</i>

9
00:01:58,400 --> 00:02:01,551
<i>He played some in the minors,</i>
<i>but nothing came of it.</i>

10
00:02:02,080 --> 00:02:03,957
<i>Moved to Brooklyn in '35...</i>

11
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:06,196
<i>...married Mom in '38...</i>

12
00:02:06,280 --> 00:02:08,714
<i>...was already an old man</i>
<i>at the naval yards...</i>

13
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:10,836
<i>...when I was born in 1952.</i>

14
00:02:11,760 --> 00:02:13,557
<i>My name's Ray Kinsella.</i>

15
00:02:13,880 --> 00:02:18,192
<i>Mom died when I was 3,</i>
<i>and I suppose Dad did the best he could.</i>

16
00:02:18,440 --> 00:02:23,389
<i>Instead of Mother Goose, I was put to bed</i>
<i>to stories of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig...</i>

17
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:25,948
<i>...and the great Shoeless Joe Jackson.</i>

18
00:02:26,520 --> 00:02:30,115
<i>Dad was a Yankees fan then,</i>
<i>so I rooted for Brooklyn.</i>

19
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:34,751
<i>But in '58, the Dodgers moved away,</i>
<i>so we had to find other reasons to fight.</i>

20
00:02:34,920 --> 00:02:35,955
<i>We did.</i>

21
00:02:36,120 --> 00:02:38,076
<i>When it came time to go to college...</i>

22
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:40,469
<i>...I picked the farthest</i>
<i>from home I could find.</i>

23
00:02:41,880 --> 00:02:45,634
<i>This drove him up the wall,</i>
<i>which, I suppose, was the point.</i>

24
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:50,073
<i>Officially my major was English,</i>
<i>but really it was the '60s.</i>

25
00:02:50,520 --> 00:02:52,829
<i>I marched, I smoked some grass...</i>

26
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:56,356
<i>...I tried to like sitar music,</i>
<i>and I met Annie.</i>

27
00:02:57,160 --> 00:03:00,436
<i>The only thing we had in common</i>
<i>was that she came from Iowa...</i>

28
00:03:00,520 --> 00:03:02,317
<i>...and I'd once heard of Iowa.</i>

29
00:03:03,280 --> 00:03:05,430
<i>After graduation,</i>
<i>we moved to the Midwest...</i>

30
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:08,114
<i>...and stayed with her family</i>
<i>as long as we could.</i>

31
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:10,077
<i>Almost a full afternoon.</i>

32
00:03:10,960 --> 00:03:13,679
<i>Annie and I got married in June of '74.</i>

33
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:15,797
<i>Dad died that fall.</i>

34
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:18,630
<i>A few years later, Karin was born.</i>

35
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:20,836
<i>She smelled weird,</i>
<i>but we loved her anyway.</i>

36
00:03:21,480 --> 00:03:25,234
<i>Then Annie got the crazy idea</i>
<i>that she could talk me into buying a farm.</i>

37
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:29,750
<i>I'm 36 years old, I love my family,</i>
<i>I love baseball...</i>

38
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,354
<i>...and I'm about to become a farmer.</i>

39
00:03:32,920 --> 00:03:35,070
<i>But until I heard the voice...</i>

40
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:38,711
<i>...I'd never done a crazy thing</i>
<i>in my whole life.</i>

41
00:04:14,480 --> 00:04:17,711
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

42
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:39,111
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

43
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:48,913
Hey, Annie!

44
00:04:49,400 --> 00:04:52,039
- Annie, what was that?
- What was what?

45
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:56,509
That voice just now. What was it?

46
00:04:59,720 --> 00:05:01,517
We didn't hear anything.

47
00:05:05,320 --> 00:05:06,548
All right.

48
00:05:09,640 --> 00:05:12,871
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

49
00:05:18,040 --> 00:05:21,112
- Okay, you must have heard that!
- Sorry.

50
00:05:21,560 --> 00:05:23,596
Hey, come on in to dinner.

51
00:05:24,080 --> 00:05:25,559
Let's go, pumpkin.

52
00:05:44,440 --> 00:05:46,635
Is there a sound truck on the highway?

53
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:49,518
Nope. Hey, Karin, dinner's ready!

54
00:05:50,480 --> 00:05:52,789
- Kids with a radio?
- Nope.

55
00:05:53,600 --> 00:05:57,115
- Are you really hearing voices?
- Just one.

56
00:05:58,480 --> 00:05:59,913
What did it say?

57
00:06:01,320 --> 00:06:03,390
"If you build it, he will come."

58
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:09,995
- If you build what, who will come?
- He didn't say.

59
00:06:11,360 --> 00:06:14,511
- I hate it when that happens.
- Me, too.

60
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:31,631
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

61
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:47,758
Build what? What is this?

62
00:06:52,280 --> 00:06:53,998
It's okay, honey.

63
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:57,308
I'm just talking to the corn field.

64
00:07:01,520 --> 00:07:03,750
<i>Anyway, I was walking</i>
<i>down along the street...</i>

65
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:06,070
<i>...and I heard this voice saying...</i>

66
00:07:06,160 --> 00:07:07,798
<i>..."Good evening, Mr. Dowd."</i>

67
00:07:07,880 --> 00:07:10,235
<i>Well, I turned around...</i>

68
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:14,755
<i>...and here was this big six-foot rabbit</i>
<i>leaning up against the lamppost.</i>

69
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,073
- Why did you do that? It was funny.
- Trust me. It's not funny.

70
00:07:23,280 --> 00:07:25,589
The man is sick. Very sick.

71
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:27,910
Honey, get your book bag. Let's go!

72
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,754
I'll take her today.
I've got some errands to do in town.

73
00:07:32,320 --> 00:07:33,355
Far-out.

74
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:42,392
- What if the voice calls while you're gone?
- Take a message.

75
00:07:43,040 --> 00:07:45,076
- 'Bye.
- 'Bye.

76
00:07:45,400 --> 00:07:46,435
'Bye.

77
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:51,028
In all those years, did you ever...

78
00:07:51,520 --> 00:07:54,751
It's just I've heard
that sometimes farmers in the field...

79
00:07:54,840 --> 00:07:57,274
They hear things. You know, voices.

80
00:07:57,360 --> 00:08:01,319
- You hearing voices?
- No. It's just I heard some farmers do.

81
00:08:01,400 --> 00:08:05,678
I, of course, don't, so I was wondering
if I was doing something wrong.

82
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:10,234
Did you ever hear voices out there?

83
00:08:10,320 --> 00:08:13,710
- Who's hearing voices?
- Ray is. Out in the fields.

84
00:08:13,800 --> 00:08:15,153
No, I'm not.

85
00:08:15,840 --> 00:08:16,829
I'm...

86
00:08:19,720 --> 00:08:21,233
Noises.

87
00:08:21,480 --> 00:08:23,516
That darned tractor...

88
00:08:24,280 --> 00:08:27,795
I'm just going to get some 3-in-1oil.
That ought to do it.

89
00:08:28,400 --> 00:08:31,073
Nice talking to you.

90
00:08:57,680 --> 00:09:00,399
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

91
00:09:00,720 --> 00:09:03,712
All right, that's it! Who the...

92
00:09:05,040 --> 00:09:07,634
Who are you? What do you want from me?

93
00:09:07,760 --> 00:09:08,795
Son of a bitch.

94
00:09:08,880 --> 00:09:12,111
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

95
00:09:13,920 --> 00:09:15,512
If you build it...

96
00:09:23,760 --> 00:09:25,273
If you build it...

97
00:09:32,240 --> 00:09:33,468
...he will come.

98
00:10:00,520 --> 00:10:03,193
You don't suppose
this is like an acid flashback?

99
00:10:04,360 --> 00:10:05,509
I never took acid.

100
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:08,751
Maybe you will someday.
It's like a flash-forward.

101
00:10:09,560 --> 00:10:11,073
Annie, there's more.

102
00:10:11,160 --> 00:10:13,754
Honey, why don't you eat a little bit?

103
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:18,792
I think I know what
"If you build it, he will come" means.

104
00:10:18,880 --> 00:10:21,474
Why do I not think
this is such a good thing?

105
00:10:22,240 --> 00:10:26,199
I think it means
that if I build a baseball field out there...

106
00:10:27,080 --> 00:10:30,789
...Shoeless Joe Jackson
will come back and play ball again.

107
00:10:32,440 --> 00:10:33,873
You're kidding?

108
00:10:41,400 --> 00:10:42,389
You're kidding.

109
00:10:45,240 --> 00:10:47,595
Boy, I thought my family was crazy...

110
00:10:47,680 --> 00:10:49,989
...but this is the craziest thing
I've ever heard.

111
00:10:50,080 --> 00:10:51,513
I know it's totally nuts.

112
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:55,309
- I mean, Shoeless Joe!
- He's dead. Died in '51. He's dead.

113
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:57,960
- They suspended him, right?
- Right.

114
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:01,551
- He's still dead?
- As far as I know.

115
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:07,156
Did you know Babe Ruth copied his swing?

116
00:11:09,160 --> 00:11:11,276
If I did, I've forgotten it.

117
00:11:16,840 --> 00:11:19,718
He was supposed to be
so graceful and agile.

118
00:11:20,360 --> 00:11:22,999
I'd actually like to see him play again...

119
00:11:23,080 --> 00:11:26,231
...to let him play, to right an old wrong.

120
00:11:26,320 --> 00:11:28,880
Wait. Wait a minute.

121
00:11:31,120 --> 00:11:35,352
- Are you actually thinking of doing this?
- No.

122
00:11:36,640 --> 00:11:40,189
I can't think of one good reason
why I should, but...

123
00:11:48,120 --> 00:11:51,795
I'm 36. I have a wife,
a child, and a mortgage...

124
00:11:51,880 --> 00:11:54,678
...and I'm scared to death
I'm turning into my father.

125
00:11:56,040 --> 00:11:57,917
What does he have to do with all this?

126
00:11:59,800 --> 00:12:02,360
I never forgave him for getting old.

127
00:12:05,080 --> 00:12:07,878
By the time he was as old as I am now...

128
00:12:08,320 --> 00:12:10,038
...he was ancient.

129
00:12:12,240 --> 00:12:17,189
He must have had dreams,
but he never did anything about them.

130
00:12:18,360 --> 00:12:21,477
For all I know,
he may have even heard voices, too...

131
00:12:22,720 --> 00:12:25,314
...but he sure didn't listen to them.

132
00:12:25,520 --> 00:12:29,433
The man never did one spontaneous thing
in all the years I knew him.

133
00:12:30,720 --> 00:12:33,792
I'm afraid of that happening to me...

134
00:12:35,360 --> 00:12:37,999
...and something tells me
this may be my last chance...

135
00:12:38,080 --> 00:12:39,991
...to do something about it.

136
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:45,156
I want to build that field.

137
00:12:47,360 --> 00:12:48,918
Do you think I'm crazy?

138
00:12:49,960 --> 00:12:51,075
Yes.

139
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:59,637
But I also think
if you really feel you should do this...

140
00:13:02,080 --> 00:13:04,150
...then you should do it.

141
00:13:17,840 --> 00:13:21,594
- What the hell is he doing?
- He's plowing under his corn.

142
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:23,035
Why?

143
00:13:28,920 --> 00:13:32,435
Ty Cobb called him
the greatest left fielder of all time.

144
00:13:32,640 --> 00:13:36,553
He said his glove
was the place where triples go to die.

145
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:38,951
- Could he hit?
- Could he hit?

146
00:13:39,040 --> 00:13:41,759
Lifetime average .356,
third highest in history.

147
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:43,752
Why'd they call him "Shoeless Joe"?

148
00:13:44,680 --> 00:13:46,033
When he was in the minors...

149
00:13:46,120 --> 00:13:48,839
...he bought a new pair of spikes
and hurt his feet.

150
00:13:48,920 --> 00:13:52,549
<i>In the 6th inning, he took them off</i>
<i>and played in his socks.</i>

151
00:13:52,640 --> 00:13:56,918
<i>The players kidded him, called him</i>
<i>"Shoeless Joe" and the name stuck.</i>

152
00:13:57,760 --> 00:13:59,398
He's going to lose his farm.

153
00:13:59,480 --> 00:14:00,629
Damned fool.

154
00:14:00,720 --> 00:14:03,871
<i>Then in 1919,</i>
<i>his team the Chicago White Sox...</i>

155
00:14:03,960 --> 00:14:05,996
<i>...threw the World Series.</i>

156
00:14:06,080 --> 00:14:09,595
- <i>What's "threw"?</i>
- <i>It means they lost it on purpose.</i>

157
00:14:09,680 --> 00:14:11,671
<i>Gamblers paid them to.</i>

158
00:14:11,760 --> 00:14:13,910
<i>Except Shoeless Joe.</i>

159
00:14:14,200 --> 00:14:17,670
<i>He did take their money,</i>
<i>but nobody ever proved he did one thing...</i>

160
00:14:17,760 --> 00:14:19,318
<i>...to lose those games.</i>

161
00:14:20,760 --> 00:14:24,673
If he threw it, how do you explain
that he hit .375 for the Series...

162
00:14:24,760 --> 00:14:26,512
...and committed no errors?

163
00:14:26,600 --> 00:14:27,589
I can't.

164
00:14:27,680 --> 00:14:30,148
Twelve hits including
the Series' only home run...

165
00:14:30,240 --> 00:14:32,470
...and they said he's trying to lose?

166
00:14:32,560 --> 00:14:33,675
It's ridiculous.

167
00:14:34,280 --> 00:14:37,158
<i>The commissioner of baseball</i>
<i>suspended eight of the players...</i>

168
00:14:37,240 --> 00:14:40,152
<i>...including the great Shoeless Joe</i>
<i>Jackson, for life.</i>

169
00:14:40,240 --> 00:14:41,832
<i>What's "suspend"?</i>

170
00:14:42,840 --> 00:14:45,912
<i>It means they never</i>
<i>let him play the game again.</i>

171
00:14:48,600 --> 00:14:50,636
My father said he saw him years later...

172
00:14:50,720 --> 00:14:54,872
...playing under a made-up name
in some 10th-rate league in Carolina.

173
00:14:55,160 --> 00:14:58,357
He'd put on 50 pounds,
and his spring was gone from his step...

174
00:14:58,440 --> 00:15:00,271
...but he could still hit.

175
00:15:01,120 --> 00:15:04,396
Dad used to say
nobody could hit like Shoeless Joe.

176
00:15:05,720 --> 00:15:08,473
I think that's the first time
I've ever seen you smile...

177
00:15:08,560 --> 00:15:10,869
...when you mentioned your father.

178
00:15:24,120 --> 00:15:27,317
I have just created something
totally illogical.

179
00:15:30,760 --> 00:15:32,910
That's what I like about it.

180
00:15:35,280 --> 00:15:37,032
Am I completely nuts?

181
00:15:39,680 --> 00:15:41,318
Not completely.

182
00:15:42,600 --> 00:15:44,989
It's a good baseball field, Ray.

183
00:15:45,840 --> 00:15:48,115
It's kind of pretty, isn't it?

184
00:16:10,080 --> 00:16:11,354
Any sign?

185
00:16:14,040 --> 00:16:16,679
Something's going to happen out there.

186
00:16:17,360 --> 00:16:18,793
I can feel it.

187
00:16:37,680 --> 00:16:41,229
<i>So, for the veteran southpaw,</i>
<i>his summer of woes continues.</i>

188
00:16:41,440 --> 00:16:43,271
<i>That's four straight hits in the inning.</i>

189
00:16:43,360 --> 00:16:45,999
Daddy, what's a "southpaw"?

190
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:50,710
It means a left-handed pitcher, honey.

191
00:16:52,600 --> 00:16:55,034
- So how bad is it?
- Well.

192
00:16:56,560 --> 00:17:00,519
Considering how much less acreage
we have for corn, I say we'll probably...

193
00:17:01,880 --> 00:17:03,711
...almost break even.

194
00:17:07,680 --> 00:17:10,399
We used up all our savings on that field.

195
00:17:10,960 --> 00:17:13,474
- Daddy?
- Just a minute, Karin.

196
00:17:17,920 --> 00:17:20,878
So what are you saying?
We can't keep the field?

197
00:17:23,560 --> 00:17:26,120
Makes it real hard to keep the farm.

198
00:17:30,600 --> 00:17:32,750
- Daddy.
- In a minute, Karin!

199
00:17:33,920 --> 00:17:35,956
There's a man out there on your lawn.

200
00:18:21,760 --> 00:18:25,196
I'll put up some coffee.
Why don't you go on outside?

201
00:20:18,440 --> 00:20:19,509
Sorry.

202
00:20:23,000 --> 00:20:25,116
I'll get some out there.

203
00:20:54,520 --> 00:20:55,635
Hi.

204
00:20:57,520 --> 00:20:58,748
Ray Kinsella.

205
00:21:00,880 --> 00:21:02,393
Joe Jackson.

206
00:21:29,400 --> 00:21:32,198
I bet it's good to be playing again.

207
00:21:38,680 --> 00:21:41,069
Getting thrown out of baseball...

208
00:21:42,480 --> 00:21:45,233
...was like having part of me amputated.

209
00:21:47,080 --> 00:21:49,275
I've heard that old men wake up...

210
00:21:49,360 --> 00:21:53,319
...and scratch itchy legs
that have been dust for over 50 years.

211
00:21:54,120 --> 00:21:55,553
That was me.

212
00:21:57,040 --> 00:21:58,996
I'd wake up at night...

213
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:03,037
...with the smell
of the ballpark in my nose...

214
00:22:03,840 --> 00:22:06,752
...with the cool of the grass on my feet...

215
00:22:08,920 --> 00:22:10,956
...the thrill of the grass.

216
00:22:18,360 --> 00:22:19,793
Can you pitch?

217
00:22:21,680 --> 00:22:22,795
Yeah.

218
00:22:24,440 --> 00:22:25,589
Not bad.

219
00:22:40,920 --> 00:22:44,390
- Don't we need a catcher?
- Not if you get it near the plate.

220
00:22:46,320 --> 00:22:47,435
Right.

221
00:22:59,560 --> 00:23:01,949
I'm pitching to Shoeless Joe Jackson.

222
00:23:10,680 --> 00:23:11,669
Nice hit.

223
00:23:26,240 --> 00:23:27,912
See if you can hit my curve.

224
00:23:37,400 --> 00:23:41,439
- You can hit the curve ball.
- Put one right here.

225
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:44,635
Right.

226
00:23:58,040 --> 00:23:59,951
Right, you're a low-ball hitter.

227
00:24:00,560 --> 00:24:02,710
Man, I did love this game.

228
00:24:05,040 --> 00:24:07,270
I'd have played for food money.

229
00:24:08,440 --> 00:24:12,149
It was the game, the sounds, the smells.

230
00:24:14,240 --> 00:24:18,552
Did you ever hold a ball
or a glove to your face?

231
00:24:19,560 --> 00:24:20,549
Yeah.

232
00:24:21,080 --> 00:24:24,868
I used to love traveling on the trains
from town to town.

233
00:24:26,400 --> 00:24:30,473
The hotels, brass spittoons in the lobbies...

234
