469
00:41:56,440 --> 00:42:00,479
I feel it as strongly as I've felt anything
in my life. There's a reason.

470
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:03,074
What? Just tell me what it is.

471
00:42:03,280 --> 00:42:07,239
Something's going to happen at the game.
There's something at Fenway Park.

472
00:42:07,320 --> 00:42:10,471
I got to be there
with Terence Mann to find it out.

473
00:42:11,600 --> 00:42:15,354
Is Fenway the one
with the big green wall in left field?

474
00:42:16,200 --> 00:42:17,428
Yeah.

475
00:42:18,840 --> 00:42:21,752
I dreamt last night
you were at Fenway with Terence Mann.

476
00:42:23,080 --> 00:42:25,230
- Was I sitting on the first base side?
- Yes.

477
00:42:25,680 --> 00:42:27,557
About halfway up on the aisle?

478
00:42:27,640 --> 00:42:30,074
- Yeah. Eating a hot dog.
- Eating a hot dog.

479
00:42:30,160 --> 00:42:33,357
- I had the same dream.
- I'll help you pack.

480
00:42:59,240 --> 00:43:01,879
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella.

481
00:43:02,480 --> 00:43:03,959
Hi. No.

482
00:43:04,080 --> 00:43:08,392
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella.
It's a great pleasure to finally get to...

483
00:43:08,680 --> 00:43:11,319
Hi, I'm Ray Kinsella. I'm a big fan of yours.

484
00:43:11,720 --> 00:43:12,630
Hi.

485
00:43:15,960 --> 00:43:19,873
How do you do, Mr. Mann?
I have to take you to a base...

486
00:43:21,200 --> 00:43:24,909
All right, stupid,
put your hands up and get in the trunk.

487
00:43:25,080 --> 00:43:26,752
Good.

488
00:43:28,800 --> 00:43:31,678
He lives right around here.
Do you know him?

489
00:43:32,320 --> 00:43:35,551
He's sort of a tall black man.
I'm a friend of his.

490
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:40,357
If he was much of a friend,
he'd have given you the directions himself.

491
00:43:42,840 --> 00:43:45,070
That's a good point. Thank you.

492
00:43:47,040 --> 00:43:50,476
I don't know where he lives.
Get away from me.

493
00:43:50,560 --> 00:43:54,997
I ain't going to tell you nothing.
Go away. You're a pest.

494
00:43:59,240 --> 00:44:01,390
Two blocks down, right-hand side.

495
00:44:01,480 --> 00:44:04,870
First door that doesn't have
a chicken in the window is his.

496
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:06,399
No chicken.

497
00:44:49,480 --> 00:44:50,469
Who the hell are you?

498
00:44:54,400 --> 00:44:55,833
Sir, my name's Ray Kinsella.

499
00:45:15,280 --> 00:45:19,159
- We got a learning disability here?
- If I could just have one minute, please.

500
00:45:19,640 --> 00:45:23,758
I can't tell you the secret of life,
and I don't have any answers for you.

501
00:45:24,080 --> 00:45:27,390
I don't give interviews,
and I'm no longer a public figure.

502
00:45:27,600 --> 00:45:30,433
I just want to be left alone, so piss off.

503
00:45:31,280 --> 00:45:33,271
Wait! Wait!

504
00:45:33,920 --> 00:45:36,036
I've come 1,500 miles to see you...

505
00:45:36,120 --> 00:45:39,635
...at the risk of losing my home
and alienating my wife.

506
00:45:39,840 --> 00:45:43,753
All I'm asking is one minute. Please.

507
00:45:47,880 --> 00:45:48,915
One minute.

508
00:45:58,040 --> 00:46:00,838
I understand your desire for privacy...

509
00:46:01,760 --> 00:46:04,638
...and I wouldn't intrude
if this weren't extremely important.

510
00:46:05,120 --> 00:46:08,635
Oh, God. I don't do causes anymore.

511
00:46:09,200 --> 00:46:12,988
This isn't a cause.
I don't need money or an endorsement.

512
00:46:13,320 --> 00:46:14,594
Refreshing.

513
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:16,956
You once wrote, "There comes a time...

514
00:46:17,040 --> 00:46:19,873
"...when all the cosmic tumblers
have clicked into place...

515
00:46:19,960 --> 00:46:22,758
"...and the universe
opens itself up for a few seconds...

516
00:46:22,920 --> 00:46:24,592
"...to show you what's possible."

517
00:46:25,160 --> 00:46:27,958
- Oh, my God!
- What?

518
00:46:28,360 --> 00:46:31,238
- You're from the '60s.
- Well, yeah. Actually...

519
00:46:32,560 --> 00:46:33,879
Out!

520
00:46:33,960 --> 00:46:37,111
Back to the '60s!
There's no place for you here in the future.

521
00:46:37,200 --> 00:46:38,838
Get back while you still can!

522
00:46:41,960 --> 00:46:44,315
You've changed, you know that?

523
00:46:44,920 --> 00:46:48,959
Yes, I suppose I have.
How about this? Peace, love, dope.

524
00:46:49,040 --> 00:46:50,758
Now get the hell out of here!

525
00:47:34,080 --> 00:47:37,311
- You've really pissed me off.
- Just hold it right there.

526
00:47:37,680 --> 00:47:39,352
I didn't want to do it this way.

527
00:47:39,640 --> 00:47:42,916
- What the hell is that?
- It's a gun, what do you think it is?

528
00:47:43,080 --> 00:47:45,514
- It's your finger.
- No, it's a gun.

529
00:47:45,760 --> 00:47:48,911
- Let me see it.
- I'm not going to show you my gun.

530
00:47:49,480 --> 00:47:52,790
I'm not going to hurt you.
I just need you to come with me...

531
00:47:54,200 --> 00:47:55,269
What are you doing?

532
00:47:55,760 --> 00:47:58,228
I'll beat you with a crowbar
until you go away.

533
00:47:58,480 --> 00:48:00,516
Wait! You can't do that.

534
00:48:00,720 --> 00:48:04,156
There are rules here?
Oh, no. There are no rules here.

535
00:48:05,000 --> 00:48:06,718
You're a pacifist!

536
00:48:11,440 --> 00:48:12,714
Shit.

537
00:48:13,360 --> 00:48:15,271
Thank you.

538
00:48:16,400 --> 00:48:19,631
So, what? You're kidnapping me?
What's the deal here?

539
00:48:23,720 --> 00:48:26,280
I was hoping I could just convince you
to come with me.

540
00:48:26,520 --> 00:48:27,873
So you are kidnapping me?

541
00:48:29,480 --> 00:48:32,074
I have to take you to a baseball game.

542
00:48:32,640 --> 00:48:33,629
You what?

543
00:48:34,480 --> 00:48:37,153
Tonight's game. Red Sox, A's.

544
00:48:37,600 --> 00:48:38,715
Why?

545
00:48:39,840 --> 00:48:41,273
Something will happen there.

546
00:48:41,360 --> 00:48:44,432
I don't know what,
but we'll find out when it does.

547
00:48:46,920 --> 00:48:48,069
My name's Ray Kinsella.

548
00:48:48,160 --> 00:48:51,948
You used my father's name
for a character in one of your stories.

549
00:48:52,040 --> 00:48:53,075
John Kinsella.

550
00:48:53,680 --> 00:48:56,319
You're seeing a whole team
of psychiatrists, aren't you?

551
00:48:56,440 --> 00:49:00,797
I don't blame you for thinking that,
but no, I'm not.

552
00:49:01,640 --> 00:49:04,791
I swear to God,
I'm the least crazy person I've ever known.

553
00:49:05,440 --> 00:49:08,318
Why are you kidnapping me
to a baseball game?

554
00:49:09,400 --> 00:49:13,075
- May I?
- Oh, please. Want a cup of coffee?

555
00:49:14,440 --> 00:49:15,509
No.

556
00:49:15,800 --> 00:49:17,472
Want some cookies?

557
00:49:19,200 --> 00:49:20,315
No.

558
00:49:21,600 --> 00:49:23,431
I read an interview you gave...

559
00:49:23,520 --> 00:49:26,398
...about how you always dreamed
of playing at Ebbets Field...

560
00:49:26,480 --> 00:49:29,278
...and how sad you felt
when they tore it down.

561
00:49:29,400 --> 00:49:30,549
I never said that.

562
00:49:31,760 --> 00:49:32,829
You didn't?

563
00:49:33,160 --> 00:49:35,355
I don't even recall thinking that.

564
00:49:39,960 --> 00:49:41,109
Weird.

565
00:49:46,840 --> 00:49:49,035
This whole thing is so weird.

566
00:49:50,880 --> 00:49:52,996
Then why go through with it?

567
00:49:55,840 --> 00:49:57,558
It's a long story.

568
00:50:02,000 --> 00:50:05,629
But it's a really good story.
I'll tell you on the way.

569
00:50:06,160 --> 00:50:08,549
- I'm not getting rid of you, am I?
- No.

570
00:50:08,640 --> 00:50:12,872
If you come to this game with me,
I swear I'll never bother you again.

571
00:50:13,360 --> 00:50:15,396
Not even a Christmas card.

572
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:25,991
So what do you do with yourself
these days?

573
00:50:26,080 --> 00:50:29,197
I live, I work. I learned how to cook.

574
00:50:30,200 --> 00:50:32,714
I take walks and watch sunsets.

575
00:50:34,040 --> 00:50:35,871
Don't you miss being involved?

576
00:50:36,400 --> 00:50:39,312
I was the East Coast distributor
of involved.

577
00:50:39,840 --> 00:50:42,513
I ate it and drank it and breathed it.

578
00:50:42,640 --> 00:50:45,359
Then they killed Martin, and Bobby...

579
00:50:46,000 --> 00:50:48,355
...they elected Tricky Dick twice...

580
00:50:48,480 --> 00:50:51,119
...and now people like you think
I must be miserable...

581
00:50:51,200 --> 00:50:54,510
...because I'm not involved anymore.
I've got news for you.

582
00:50:54,600 --> 00:50:56,909
I spent all my misery years ago.

583
00:50:57,120 --> 00:51:00,954
I have no more pain left for any of you.
I gave at the office.

584
00:51:02,600 --> 00:51:04,397
So what do you want?

585
00:51:04,760 --> 00:51:07,274
I want them to stop
looking to me for answers...

586
00:51:07,360 --> 00:51:10,511
...begging me to speak again,
write again, be a leader.

587
00:51:10,600 --> 00:51:12,955
I want them to start thinking
for themselves.

588
00:51:13,040 --> 00:51:14,871
And I want my privacy.

589
00:51:16,040 --> 00:51:19,157
No, I meant what do you want?

590
00:51:25,720 --> 00:51:27,312
Dog and a beer.

591
00:51:29,240 --> 00:51:32,277
- Two.
- $7.

592
00:51:32,960 --> 00:51:34,313
Okay, I understand you.

593
00:51:34,440 --> 00:51:36,908
You should be entitled
to as much privacy as you want.

594
00:51:37,000 --> 00:51:38,911
But why stop writing?

595
00:51:39,560 --> 00:51:44,634
I haven't published a word in 17 years,
and still I have to endure lunatics like you.

596
00:51:44,720 --> 00:51:48,190
What do you think would happen
if I suddenly came out with a new book?

597
00:51:48,360 --> 00:51:50,078
They'd bleed me dry.

598
00:52:03,640 --> 00:52:05,756
<i>Go the distance.</i>

599
00:52:13,640 --> 00:52:15,790
<i>Go the distance.</i>

600
00:52:34,880 --> 00:52:35,869
What's the matter?

601
00:52:39,720 --> 00:52:42,359
- You didn't see that?
- See what?

602
00:52:49,360 --> 00:52:51,510
I'm sorry.
I guess you didn't have to be here.

603
00:52:51,600 --> 00:52:52,749
What?

604
00:52:55,800 --> 00:52:58,268
Whenever you want to go, we can go.

605
00:52:58,800 --> 00:53:00,392
Fine. Let's go.

606
00:53:44,920 --> 00:53:47,354
What is it you're not telling me?

607
00:53:48,320 --> 00:53:51,232
I've already taken up
too much of your time.

608
00:54:02,720 --> 00:54:04,756
I wish I had your passion.

609
00:54:05,040 --> 00:54:08,510
Misdirected though it might be,
it is still a passion.

610
00:54:08,600 --> 00:54:11,637
I used to feel that way about things, but...

611
00:54:14,560 --> 00:54:17,950
- You got another message, didn't you?
- You'll think I'm crazy.

612
00:54:18,160 --> 00:54:20,958
I already think you're crazy.
What did it say?

613
00:54:24,360 --> 00:54:27,477
It said, "The man's done enough.
Leave him alone."

614
00:54:47,120 --> 00:54:48,678
Moonlight Graham.

615
00:54:49,720 --> 00:54:52,314
- You saw it.
- Saw what?

616
00:54:52,920 --> 00:54:57,516
You saw it. New York Giants, 1922.
He played one game. He never got to bat.

617
00:54:57,600 --> 00:54:59,158
- You saw it!
- What did I see?

618
00:54:59,240 --> 00:55:00,912
Chisholm, Minnesota.

619
00:55:01,000 --> 00:55:04,470
We were the only ones who saw it.
Did you hear the voice, too?

620
00:55:04,560 --> 00:55:05,754
It's all right to admit it.

621
00:55:05,840 --> 00:55:08,274
It's what told me to find you.
Did you hear it?

622
00:55:10,640 --> 00:55:11,993
"Go the distance"?

623
00:55:13,280 --> 00:55:17,193
- Yes. Do you know what it means?
- Yes.

624
00:55:17,280 --> 00:55:18,315
What?

625
00:55:18,400 --> 00:55:21,631
It means we're going to Minnesota
to find Moonlight Graham.

626
00:55:21,720 --> 00:55:24,678
- We're going... We?
- I must be out of my mind.

627
00:55:24,960 --> 00:55:29,112
- What do we do when we find him?
- How the hell am I supposed to know?

628
00:55:29,640 --> 00:55:31,471
That's right. You're right.

629
00:55:32,960 --> 00:55:36,430
- This is so bitchin'.
- I don't believe I'm doing this.

630
00:55:53,600 --> 00:55:56,672
<i>Hey, Annie, guess what?</i>
<i>I'm with Terence Mann.</i>

631
00:55:56,760 --> 00:55:58,716
<i>Oh, my God. You kidnapped him.</i>

632
00:55:58,840 --> 00:56:01,149
<i>No, I didn't. He wanted to.</i>

633
00:56:01,520 --> 00:56:04,512
<i>I'm really sorry,</i>
<i>but I'm going to be a few days longer.</i>

634
00:56:04,600 --> 00:56:06,033
<i>We're going to Minnesota.</i>

635
00:56:06,120 --> 00:56:08,793
<i>I don't believe this. What's in Minnesota?</i>

636
00:56:08,880 --> 00:56:11,633
An old ballplayer.
I'll explain when I get home.

637
00:56:11,720 --> 00:56:14,518
- How are things with you?
- <i>Fine.</i>

638
00:56:14,760 --> 00:56:17,558
Great. Look, Ann, I got to go, okay?

639
00:56:18,160 --> 00:56:21,550
Give Karin a hug for me, and I love you.

640
00:56:21,960 --> 00:56:23,393
I love you, too.

641
00:56:24,720 --> 00:56:26,790
Someday explain all this to me, okay?

642
00:56:26,880 --> 00:56:29,110
<i>I'll try. Bye-bye.</i>

643
00:56:29,200 --> 00:56:30,269
'Bye.

644
00:56:37,120 --> 00:56:38,439
Why didn't you tell him?

645
00:56:41,480 --> 00:56:43,516
You got no choice in the matter.

646
00:56:48,160 --> 00:56:52,836
Half a dozen Grahams.
No Archibald. No Moonlight.

647
00:56:54,480 --> 00:56:55,754
Follow me.

648
00:57:07,240 --> 00:57:08,468
Hello.

649
00:57:09,880 --> 00:57:11,632
Excuse me. Maybe you can help us.

650
00:57:11,720 --> 00:57:14,553
We're looking for an ex-baseball player,
Archibald Graham.

651
00:57:15,080 --> 00:57:18,550
- Oh, you mean Doc Graham.
- No, I think his nickname was "Moonlight."

652
00:57:18,920 --> 00:57:21,480
- That's Dr. Graham.
- Dr. Graham?

653
00:57:21,840 --> 00:57:25,833
His baseball career never amounted
to much, so he went back to school.

654
00:57:25,920 --> 00:57:27,239
His father was a doctor.

655
00:57:27,560 --> 00:57:32,236
- Do you know where we can find him?
- It's nothing bad. We're not from the IRS.

656
00:57:33,200 --> 00:57:37,159
Doc Graham is dead. He died in 1972.

657
00:57:40,680 --> 00:57:44,070
"At times children could not afford
eyeglasses or milk or clothing.

658
00:57:44,800 --> 00:57:47,519
"Yet no child was ever denied
these essentials...

659
00:57:47,600 --> 00:57:50,558
"...because, in the background,
there was always Dr. Graham.

660
00:57:50,760 --> 00:57:54,753
"Without any fanfare or publicity,
the glasses or the milk...

661
00:57:55,440 --> 00:57:59,638
"...or the ticket to the ball game
found their way into the child's pocket."

662
00:58:00,240 --> 00:58:03,437
- You wrote that.
- The day he died.

663
00:58:03,520 --> 00:58:04,873
Can I see that?

664
00:58:04,960 --> 00:58:08,396
- You're a good writer.
- So are you.

665
00:58:13,760 --> 00:58:15,398
Something's missing.

666
00:58:17,240 --> 00:58:19,993
He sounds like he was a wonderful man.

667
00:58:21,160 --> 00:58:24,277
Half the towns in North America
have a Doc Graham.

668
00:58:24,680 --> 00:58:28,195
Why do we have to travel halfway
across the country to find this one...

669
00:58:28,520 --> 00:58:30,750
...sixteen years after he died?

670
00:58:31,400 --> 00:58:33,277
There's got to be more.

671
00:58:38,920 --> 00:58:39,909
What else?

672
00:58:40,560 --> 00:58:42,869
He always wore an overcoat...

673
00:58:42,960 --> 00:58:46,555
...he had white hair,
and he always carried an umbrella.

674
00:58:46,880 --> 00:58:47,995
What was the umbrella for?

675
00:58:48,280 --> 00:58:51,477
I think it got to be a habit,
something to hang on to.

676
00:58:51,760 --> 00:58:55,799
If you asked him, he said he used it
to beat away his lady admirers.

677
00:58:56,080 --> 00:58:57,399
Tell me about his wife.

678
00:58:58,120 --> 00:58:59,394
Alicia.

679
00:59:00,800 --> 00:59:04,759
She moved to South Carolina
after Doc passed.

680
00:59:05,840 --> 00:59:08,274
She passed a couple years later.

681
00:59:09,000 --> 00:59:11,036
She always wore blue.

682
00:59:12,120 --> 00:59:16,318
The shopkeepers in town
would stock blue hats...

683
00:59:16,800 --> 00:59:21,271
...because they knew if Doc walked by,
he'd buy one.

684
00:59:23,160 --> 00:59:25,754
When they cleaned out his office...

685
00:59:25,840 --> 00:59:28,593
...they found boxes of blue hats...

686
00:59:30,320 --> 00:59:33,073
...that he never got around to give her.

687
00:59:33,280 --> 00:59:35,032
I'll bet you didn't know that.

688
00:59:35,960 --> 00:59:38,155
No, I didn't.

689
00:59:40,760 --> 00:59:45,436
No screwing, no drinking,
no opium, no midnight abortions.

690
00:59:46,440 --> 00:59:50,115
No illegitimate children, no shady finances.

691
00:59:50,720 --> 00:59:52,756
You sound disappointed.

692
00:59:53,800 --> 00:59:57,156
Shoeless Joe had a problem.
That's why he needed you.

693
00:59:57,480 --> 00:59:59,391
This guy doesn't need us.

694
01:00:03,120 --> 01:00:05,270
Do you know you're missing?

695
01:00:09,520 --> 01:00:10,873
Oh, God.

696
01:00:12,040 --> 01:00:16,272
"His father, who lives in Baltimore,
notified police after receiving...

697
01:00:16,360 --> 01:00:19,318
"...no answer to repeated telephone calls."
Shoot.

698
01:00:20,080 --> 01:00:21,308
I better call him.

699
01:00:21,720 --> 01:00:24,439
- You want me to...
- Thanks.

700
01:00:30,840 --> 01:00:33,434
I'm taking a walk. Be back in a while.

701
01:00:38,920 --> 01:00:40,831
What do I tell him?

702
01:01:07,280 --> 01:01:08,349
"This year's"?

703
01:01:48,840 --> 01:01:50,353
Dr. Graham?

704
01:01:58,680 --> 01:01:59,999
Dr. Graham?

705
01:02:04,280 --> 01:02:07,078
My name's Ray Kinsella. I'm from Iowa.

706
01:02:09,880 --> 01:02:11,279
Are you Moonlight Graham?

707
01:02:16,400 --> 01:02:19,551
No one's called me Moonlight Graham
in 50 years.

708
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:23,877
I've come a very long way to see you.

709
01:02:24,480 --> 01:02:27,756
I couldn't sleep tonight.
Usually I sleep like a baby.

710
01:02:27,840 --> 01:02:29,956
I told Alicia I was going to take a walk.

711
01:02:32,280 --> 01:02:35,989
Do you mind if I join you?
I'd like to talk to you.

712
01:02:37,160 --> 01:02:38,878
Let's walk over to my office.

713
01:02:40,800 --> 01:02:42,677
What do you want to talk to me about?

714
01:02:42,840 --> 01:02:46,674
When you got to the majors,
you played only one inning of one game.

715
01:02:46,760 --> 01:02:48,716
What happened with you?

716
01:02:49,600 --> 01:02:51,795
It was the last day of the season.

717
01:02:51,880 --> 01:02:54,189
Bottom of the eighth inning,
we were way ahead.

718
01:02:54,280 --> 01:02:58,353
I'd been up with the club for three weeks,
but I hadn't seen any action.

719
01:02:58,440 --> 01:03:01,671
Suddenly old John McGraw
points a bony finger in my direction...

720
01:03:01,760 --> 01:03:03,637
...and he says, "Right field."

721
01:03:04,800 --> 01:03:07,314
I jumped up like I was sitting on a spring.

722
01:03:07,400 --> 01:03:11,234
Grabbed my glove, and ran out on the field.

723
01:03:13,720 --> 01:03:15,756
Did you get to make a play?

724
01:03:15,840 --> 01:03:18,673
They never hit the ball out of the infield.

725
01:03:20,080 --> 01:03:22,753
The game ended. The season was over.

726
01:03:23,280 --> 01:03:25,589
I knew they'd send me back down.

727
01:03:26,080 --> 01:03:29,277
I couldn't bear the thought
of another year in the minors.

728
01:03:29,440 --> 01:03:32,318
So I decided to hang them up.

729
01:03:34,800 --> 01:03:37,189
- Go on. Sit down.
- Thank you.

730
01:03:39,280 --> 01:03:41,157
So what was that like?

731
01:03:43,280 --> 01:03:46,352
It was like coming this close
to your dreams...

732
01:03:46,720 --> 01:03:50,429
...and then watching them brush past you,
like a stranger in a crowd.

733
01:03:50,520 --> 01:03:52,317
At the time, you don't think much of it.

734
01:03:52,400 --> 01:03:55,790
We don't recognize our most significant
moments while they're happening.

735
01:03:56,360 --> 01:03:59,636
Back then I thought,
"Well, there'll be other days."

736
01:03:59,880 --> 01:04:02,633
I didn't realize that was the only day.

737
01:04:04,480 --> 01:04:07,552
And now, I want to ask you a question.

738
01:04:08,480 --> 01:04:12,758
What's so interesting about half an inning
that would make you come from Iowa...

739
01:04:12,840 --> 01:04:15,593
...to talk to me about it
50 years after it happened.

740
01:04:17,040 --> 01:04:19,679
I didn't really know till just now...

741
01:04:20,680 --> 01:04:24,559
...but I think it's to ask you,
if you could do anything you wanted...

742
01:04:24,680 --> 01:04:26,989
...if you could have a wish...

743
01:04:30,560 --> 01:04:33,711
And you're the kind of man
who could grant me that wish?

744
01:04:34,960 --> 01:04:37,554
I don't know. I'm just asking.

745
01:04:39,280 --> 01:04:43,353
You know,
I never got to bat in the major leagues.

746
01:04:43,600 --> 01:04:46,398
I'd have liked to have had that chance,
just once...

747
01:04:46,560 --> 01:04:48,835
...to stare down a big-league pitcher.

748
01:04:48,920 --> 01:04:53,072
Stare him down,
then just as he goes into his windup, wink.

749
01:04:53,600 --> 01:04:55,955
Make him think you know
something he doesn't.

750
01:04:56,040 --> 01:04:57,712
That's what I wish for.

751
01:04:57,800 --> 01:05:01,588
The chance to squint at a sky so blue
that it hurts your eyes to look at it.

752
01:05:01,680 --> 01:05:04,513
To feel the tingle in your arms
as you connect with the ball.

753
01:05:04,600 --> 01:05:07,068
To run the bases,
stretch a double into a triple...

754
01:05:07,160 --> 01:05:09,720
...and flop face first into third.

755
01:05:09,880 --> 01:05:12,155
Wrap your arms around the bag.

756
01:05:12,360 --> 01:05:13,839
That's my wish.

757
01:05:17,080 --> 01:05:20,072
Is there enough magic out there
in the moonlight...

758
01:05:20,160 --> 01:05:21,832
...to make this dream come true?

759
01:05:22,520 --> 01:05:27,275
- What would you say if I said yes?
- I think I'd actually believe you.

760
01:05:29,880 --> 01:05:32,110
There's a place
where things like that happen...

761
01:05:32,200 --> 01:05:34,668
...and if you want to go, I can take you.

762
01:05:39,120 --> 01:05:42,032
This is my most special place
in all the world.

763
01:05:42,440 --> 01:05:46,592
Once a place touches you like this,
the wind never blows so cold again.

764
01:05:48,000 --> 01:05:51,436
You feel for it. Like it was your child.

765
01:05:53,120 --> 01:05:54,553
I can't leave Chisholm.

766
01:05:55,480 --> 01:05:58,278
I understand. I do.

767
01:06:00,520 --> 01:06:04,069
But I really think
you're supposed to come with us.

768
01:06:04,960 --> 01:06:06,029
No.

769
01:06:09,280 --> 01:06:10,429
But your wish?

770
01:06:11,880 --> 01:06:13,677
It'll have to stay a wish.

771
01:06:13,840 --> 01:06:17,879
I was born here, I lived here,
I'll die here, but no regrets.

772
01:06:19,040 --> 01:06:23,272
Fifty years ago, for five minutes,
you came this close.

773
01:06:23,720 --> 01:06:28,236
It would kill some men to get that close
to their dream and not touch it.

774
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:30,718
They'd consider it a tragedy.

775
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:34,709
Son, if I'd only gotten to be a doctor
for five minutes...

776
01:06:35,040 --> 01:06:36,951
...now that would have been a tragedy.

777
01:06:40,800 --> 01:06:44,759
I better be getting home.
Alicia will think I got a girlfriend.

778
01:06:45,800 --> 01:06:47,313
And he smiled.

779
01:06:49,280 --> 01:06:53,717
And then I figured, maybe we're not
supposed to take him with us.

780
01:06:54,000 --> 01:06:55,433
I don't know.

781
01:06:57,160 --> 01:06:59,993
I don't know why in the hell
we were supposed to come here.

782
01:07:00,080 --> 01:07:03,755
Maybe it's to find out
if one inning can change the world.

783
01:07:04,640 --> 01:07:07,313
- Think it did?
- It did for these people.

784
01:07:07,400 --> 01:07:10,915
If he'd gotten a hit,
he might have stayed in baseball.

785
01:07:11,520 --> 01:07:12,873
I don't know.

786
01:07:13,840 --> 01:07:17,196
Your wife called before.
She wants you to call her tonight.

787
01:07:24,880 --> 01:07:27,553
I'm fine. I'm just so glad it's you.

788
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:31,629
Listen, I talked to the bank...

789
01:07:31,720 --> 01:07:35,110
...and I asked them
if we could miss a payment or two...

790
01:07:35,320 --> 01:07:39,074
...and they told me that they had just sold
the note on the farm...

791
01:07:39,520 --> 01:07:42,478
...to Mark and his partners.

792
01:07:43,600 --> 01:07:45,352
Right. So they own the paper now.

793
01:07:45,440 --> 01:07:49,274
He says if we don't sell to them,
they're going to foreclose.

794
01:07:51,280 --> 01:07:53,350
We don't have the money.

795
01:07:53,840 --> 01:07:58,868
Look, I've got to take Mr. Mann
back to Boston first.

796
01:07:59,120 --> 01:08:02,032
- No.
- Wait a second.

797
01:08:02,800 --> 01:08:04,199
I'm going to Iowa with you.

798
01:08:08,040 --> 01:08:09,268
We're coming home.

799
01:08:13,000 --> 01:08:16,549
Hell, I can't quit now.
I got to see this ball park.

800
01:08:17,160 --> 01:08:19,754
Not everyone can see it. You might not.

801
01:08:20,720 --> 01:08:22,278
Give it a try.

802
01:08:28,040 --> 01:08:30,076
I need all the karma I can get right now.

803
01:08:36,480 --> 01:08:39,631
- Thanks. You're the first car by.
- How far you going?

804
01:08:39,720 --> 01:08:42,075
- How far you going?
- Iowa.

805
01:08:42,280 --> 01:08:46,068
If it's okay, I'll just ride along a while.
I play baseball.

806
01:08:47,800 --> 01:08:49,711
- Hop in.
- All right.

807
01:08:57,960 --> 01:08:59,712
I'm looking for a place to play.

808
01:08:59,800 --> 01:09:03,395
I heard that all through the Midwest,
they have towns with teams.

809
01:09:03,480 --> 01:09:06,756
And in some places,
they'll even find you a day job...

810
01:09:06,840 --> 01:09:09,195
...so you can play ball
nights and weekends.

811
01:09:09,320 --> 01:09:13,552
This is your lucky day, kid.
We're going someplace kind of like that.

812
01:09:14,160 --> 01:09:15,434
All right.

813
01:09:15,640 --> 01:09:19,918
- I'm Ray Kinsella. This is Terence Mann.
- Hi.

814
01:09:20,000 --> 01:09:21,752
I'm Archie Graham.

815
01:09:33,760 --> 01:09:36,991
It's funny the way he described towns
finding you a job...

816
01:09:37,080 --> 01:09:41,710
...so that you could play on their team.
They haven't done that for years.

817
01:09:41,840 --> 01:09:45,435
My dad did that for a while,
but that was in the '20s.

818
01:09:45,960 --> 01:09:47,313
What happened to your father?

819
01:09:48,000 --> 01:09:49,592
He never made it as a ballplayer...

820
01:09:49,680 --> 01:09:52,717
...so he tried to get his son
to make it for him.

821
01:09:52,800 --> 01:09:54,791
By the time I was 10, playing baseball...

822
01:09:54,880 --> 01:09:58,429
...got to be like eating vegetables
or taking out the garbage.

823
01:09:58,880 --> 01:10:01,678
So when I was 14, I started to refuse.

824
01:10:02,760 --> 01:10:04,591
Can you believe that?

825
01:10:04,720 --> 01:10:07,712
American boy refusing to have a catch
with his father?

826
01:10:07,960 --> 01:10:09,188
Why 14?

827
01:10:11,240 --> 01:10:13,629
That's when I read <i>The Boat Rocker</i>
by Terence Mann.

828
01:10:13,720 --> 01:10:14,755
God!

829
01:10:15,080 --> 01:10:16,718
I never played catch with him again.

830
01:10:16,800 --> 01:10:19,075
That's the kind of crap
people always lay on me.

831
01:10:19,160 --> 01:10:21,515
It's not my fault
you wouldn't play catch with him.

832
01:10:21,600 --> 01:10:22,794
I know.

833
01:10:25,520 --> 01:10:27,556
Anyway, when I was 17...

834
01:10:28,640 --> 01:10:32,030
...I packed my things,
said something awful, and left.

835
01:10:32,640 --> 01:10:36,110
After a while, I wanted to come home,
but I didn't know how.

836
01:10:37,080 --> 01:10:39,719
Made it back for the funeral, though.

837
01:10:49,600 --> 01:10:51,989
What was the awful thing you said?

838
01:10:53,440 --> 01:10:54,998
To your father?

839
01:10:58,360 --> 01:11:02,148
I said I could never respect a man
whose hero was a criminal.

840
01:11:03,440 --> 01:11:05,112
Who was his hero?

841
01:11:05,920 --> 01:11:07,751
Shoeless Joe Jackson.

842
01:11:10,120 --> 01:11:13,999
You knew he wasn't a criminal.
Then why did you say it?

843
01:11:15,880 --> 01:11:17,359
I was 17.

844
01:11:21,480 --> 01:11:24,756
The son of a bitch died
before I could take it back.

845
01:11:25,880 --> 01:11:27,791
Before I could tell him...

846
01:11:29,160 --> 01:11:30,559
...you know.

847
01:11:32,920 --> 01:11:34,831
He never met my wife.

848
01:11:36,560 --> 01:11:38,516
He never saw his granddaughter.

849
01:11:40,320 --> 01:11:42,117
This is your penance.

850
01:11:42,720 --> 01:11:46,315
I know. I can't bring my father back.

851
01:11:46,440 --> 01:11:49,477
So the least you can do
is bring back his hero.

852
01:11:50,520 --> 01:11:51,714
Well...

853
01:11:54,600 --> 01:11:57,637
Now I know
what everybody's purpose here is.

854
01:11:58,800 --> 01:12:00,119
Except mine.

855
01:12:30,640 --> 01:12:33,677
- Daddy!
- Karin, come here.

856
01:12:36,800 --> 01:12:37,949
Hi!

857
01:12:39,240 --> 01:12:43,233
- We missed you. Are you okay?
- Yeah. This is Terence Mann.

858
01:12:43,480 --> 01:12:44,549
Terry.

859
01:12:44,840 --> 01:12:46,034
- Welcome.
- Thank you.

860
01:12:46,120 --> 01:12:47,030
Hi, Terry.

861
01:12:47,760 --> 01:12:50,513
And this young fellow is...
This is Archie Graham.

862
01:12:51,120 --> 01:12:54,476
- Archie.
- He's come to practice with the team.

863
01:12:54,680 --> 01:12:57,752
Yeah? He's going to be able to do
a lot more than that.

864
01:12:58,040 --> 01:12:59,029
What does that mean?

865
01:13:10,720 --> 01:13:13,234
- Welcome back.
- Thanks, Joe.

866
01:13:13,320 --> 01:13:14,992
- Oh, my God.
- What?

867
01:13:15,360 --> 01:13:17,271
That's Shoeless Joe Jackson!

868
01:13:17,480 --> 01:13:20,313
Of course it is.
You mean you didn't believe me?

869
01:13:20,400 --> 01:13:23,949
I thought I did, but... Oh, my God.

870
01:13:25,120 --> 01:13:26,951
- Hi, Annie.
- Hi, Joe.

871
01:13:27,080 --> 01:13:31,915
Good to see you. Terry,
I'd like you to meet Shoeless Joe Jackson.

872
01:13:32,160 --> 01:13:34,151
Joe, Terry Mann.

873
01:13:35,200 --> 01:13:38,351
- It's a pleasure meeting you.
- The pleasure's mine.

874
01:13:38,520 --> 01:13:41,717
I hope you don't mind,
but we got tired of just having practices...

875
01:13:41,800 --> 01:13:45,634
...so we brought another team out
so we could have some real games.

876
01:13:45,720 --> 01:13:48,518
I don't mind. Where'd they come from?

877
01:13:48,880 --> 01:13:50,438
Where did we come from?

878
01:13:50,520 --> 01:13:52,875
You wouldn't believe
how many guys wanted to play.

879
01:13:52,960 --> 01:13:54,632
We had to beat 'em off with a stick.

880
01:13:54,760 --> 01:13:58,275
That's "Smokey" Joe Wood, and Mel Ott...

881
01:13:59,680 --> 01:14:01,193
...and Gil Hodges!

882
01:14:01,280 --> 01:14:02,759
Ty Cobb wanted to play.

883
01:14:02,840 --> 01:14:05,513
We couldn't stand the son of a bitch
when we were alive...

884
01:14:05,600 --> 01:14:07,352
...so we told him to stick it!

885
01:14:11,920 --> 01:14:14,639
- Are you Graham?
- Yes, sir.

886
01:14:15,240 --> 01:14:19,028
What are you doing on the sidelines?
You came to play ball, didn't you?

887
01:14:19,120 --> 01:14:20,519
Yes, sir.

888
01:14:21,120 --> 01:14:24,874
- All right. Well, go warm up.
- Yes, sir.

889
01:14:27,080 --> 01:14:28,433
Rookies.

890
01:14:29,200 --> 01:14:30,713
Unbelievable.

891
01:14:32,400 --> 01:14:34,072
It's more than that.

892
01:14:34,960 --> 01:14:36,393
It's perfect.

893
01:14:48,800 --> 01:14:49,994
Safe!

894
01:14:59,240 --> 01:15:01,151
Go, Graham! Go, kid!

895
01:15:01,240 --> 01:15:02,878
Come on, Archie!

896
01:15:02,960 --> 01:15:05,190
He looks like a baby next to those guys.

897
01:15:05,280 --> 01:15:06,315
He is.

898
01:15:16,880 --> 01:15:18,108
Let's go.

899
01:15:21,360 --> 01:15:22,634
Watch it, boy!

900
01:15:25,320 --> 01:15:27,834
Don't let him shake you up. Hang in there!

901
01:15:28,000 --> 01:15:30,958
Knuckles, what did you throw
at the kid for?

902
01:15:31,520 --> 01:15:34,159
- He winked at me.
- Don't wink, kid.

903
01:15:36,360 --> 01:15:39,352
Good thing for you
he didn't throw the fastball.

904
01:15:43,440 --> 01:15:44,793
Let's see that fastball.

905
01:15:49,360 --> 01:15:50,349
Ball.

906
01:15:50,440 --> 01:15:53,716
Hey! Come on. Give us a break!

907
01:15:54,080 --> 01:15:55,149
Hey, ump.

908
01:15:56,360 --> 01:16:00,319
- How about a warning?
- Sure. Watch out you don't get killed.

909
01:16:01,200 --> 01:16:02,349
Time!

910
01:16:03,200 --> 01:16:04,349
Time!

911
01:16:06,240 --> 01:16:10,518
Those first two were high and tight.
So what do you think the next one will be?

912
01:16:12,440 --> 01:16:15,238
Either low and away or in my ear.

913
01:16:15,360 --> 01:16:18,830
He's not going to want to load the bases.
So look for low and away.

914
01:16:18,920 --> 01:16:20,478
Right.

915
01:16:21,200 --> 01:16:23,430
But watch out for in your ear.

916
01:16:24,840 --> 01:16:26,193
- Come on, Archie!
- Let's go, kid!

917
01:16:26,280 --> 01:16:28,032
Batter, batter, batter!

918
01:16:28,120 --> 01:16:30,793
Come on, Arch. It just takes one.

919
01:16:42,320 --> 01:16:44,515
- Yeah.
- That's deep enough.

920
01:16:45,440 --> 01:16:48,113
Go! Go! Go home!

921
01:16:49,760 --> 01:16:51,716
- Safe!
- Son of a...

922
01:16:52,200 --> 01:16:55,078
Way to go, Arch! Way to go!

923
01:16:55,160 --> 01:16:57,116
Attaboy, Arch!

924
01:16:58,240 --> 01:17:00,037
This is the wave!

925
01:17:01,000 --> 01:17:03,116
- Way to go, man!
- Yeah, Archie.

926
01:17:03,400 --> 01:17:05,675
- All right.
- Archie, we need it.

927
01:17:05,960 --> 01:17:08,190
- Way to go.
- Yeah. Way to go.

928
01:17:41,800 --> 01:17:44,633
- What is this?
- What is this jerk doing?

929
01:17:44,720 --> 01:17:45,755
Hi!

930
01:17:46,520 --> 01:17:48,795
- Shit! Wreck him.
- Let me at him!

931
01:17:49,320 --> 01:17:51,117
You're interrupting the game, Mark.

932
01:17:52,800 --> 01:17:57,191
It's time to put away your little fantasies
and come down to Earth.

933
01:17:57,400 --> 01:18:00,870
- It's not a fantasy. They're real.
- Who is real?

934
01:18:01,360 --> 01:18:04,033
Shoeless Joe Jackson, the White Sox,
all of them.

935
01:18:04,600 --> 01:18:07,273
- You mean?
- No. He can't see any of them.

936
01:18:08,720 --> 01:18:10,312
Who is this, Elvis?

937
01:18:11,440 --> 01:18:12,509
Ray.

938
01:18:13,600 --> 01:18:15,716
As a matter of fact, it's Terence Mann.

939
01:18:16,280 --> 01:18:18,032
How do you do? I'm the Easter Bunny.

940
01:18:18,120 --> 01:18:21,192
- Let's settle this thing now.
- Look. I'm not selling.

941
01:18:21,280 --> 01:18:25,398
You have no money.
You have a stack of bills!

942
01:18:25,480 --> 01:18:27,789
Come fall, you got no crop to sell.

943
01:18:27,880 --> 01:18:30,997
But, I have a deal
that allows you to stay on the land.

944
01:18:31,200 --> 01:18:34,112
Daddy? We don't have to sell the farm.

945
01:18:34,440 --> 01:18:38,479
- You'll live in the house rent-free.
- What about the team...

946
01:18:38,560 --> 01:18:40,596
Do you realize how much
this land is worth?

947
01:18:40,680 --> 01:18:42,511
Yeah. Yeah.

948
01:18:44,080 --> 01:18:45,877
$2,200 an acre.

949
01:18:46,240 --> 01:18:49,994
We can't keep a useless baseball diamond
in rich farmland.

950
01:18:50,080 --> 01:18:52,116
Read my lips. We're staying, all right?

951
01:18:52,200 --> 01:18:54,714
- We're staying.
- Ray, you're bankrupt!

952
01:18:54,800 --> 01:18:57,917
I'm offering you a way to keep your home
because I love my sister.

953
01:18:58,000 --> 01:19:01,993
My partners don't care
and are ready to foreclose right now.

954
01:19:02,080 --> 01:19:05,038
Daddy, we don't have to sell the farm.

955
01:19:05,120 --> 01:19:07,236
- Karin, please!
- Just wait! Wait!

956
01:19:11,280 --> 01:19:12,918
People will come.

957
01:19:14,360 --> 01:19:17,511
- What people, sweetheart?
- From all over.

958
01:19:17,600 --> 01:19:20,398
They'll just decide to take a vacation, see?

959
01:19:20,480 --> 01:19:24,553
And they'll come to Iowa City.
They'll think it's really boring.

960
01:19:24,920 --> 01:19:28,515
So they'll want to pay us.
Like buying a ticket.

961
01:19:32,120 --> 01:19:34,793
You're not seriously listening to this,
are you?

962
01:19:34,880 --> 01:19:37,474
- Yes.
- Wait a minute.

963
01:19:38,320 --> 01:19:40,914
Why would anybody
pay money to come here?

964
01:19:41,200 --> 01:19:42,713
To watch the games.

965
01:19:43,160 --> 01:19:47,278
It will be just like when they were kids,
a long time ago.

966
01:19:47,480 --> 01:19:50,313
They'll watch the game
and remember what it was like.

967
01:19:50,840 --> 01:19:54,628
- What the hell is she talking about?
- People will come.

968
01:19:54,720 --> 01:19:56,950
All right. This is fascinating...

969
01:19:57,520 --> 01:20:00,671
...but you don't have the money
to bring the mortgage up to date.

970
01:20:00,760 --> 01:20:03,069
So, you're still going to have to sell.

971
01:20:04,160 --> 01:20:06,833
I'm sorry, Ray. We got no choice.

972
01:20:10,400 --> 01:20:13,756
People will come, Ray.

973
01:20:16,360 --> 01:20:19,591
They'll come to Iowa
for reasons they can't even fathom.

974
01:20:20,280 --> 01:20:24,558
They'll turn up your driveway,
not knowing for sure why they're doing it.

975
01:20:24,640 --> 01:20:28,030
They'll arrive at your door
as innocent as children...

976
01:20:28,120 --> 01:20:30,076
...longing for the past.

977
01:20:30,240 --> 01:20:33,789
"Of course, we won't mind
if you look around," you'll say.

978
01:20:34,760 --> 01:20:36,830
"It's only $20 per person."

979
01:20:37,240 --> 01:20:40,198
They'll pass over the money
without even thinking about it.

980
01:20:40,280 --> 01:20:43,511
For it is money they have
and peace they like.

981
01:20:43,600 --> 01:20:45,875
Ray! Just sign the papers.

982
01:20:46,360 --> 01:20:48,999
Then they'll walk off to the bleachers...

983
01:20:50,040 --> 01:20:53,635
...and sit in their shirtsleeves
on a perfect afternoon.

984
01:20:55,800 --> 01:21:00,920
They'll find they have reserved seats
somewhere along one of the baselines...

985
01:21:02,320 --> 01:21:06,552
...where they sat when they were children
and cheered their heroes...

986
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:09,036
...and they'll watch the game...

987
01:21:09,120 --> 01:21:12,829
...and it will be as if they dipped
themselves in magic waters.

988
01:21:13,200 --> 01:21:15,395
The memories will be so thick...

989
01:21:15,520 --> 01:21:18,034
...they'll have to brush them away
from their faces.

990
01:21:18,600 --> 01:21:22,275
When the bank opens in the morning,
they'll foreclose.

991
01:21:22,720 --> 01:21:24,358
People will come, Ray.

992
01:21:24,600 --> 01:21:28,354
You're broke, Ray.
You sell now, or you lose everything.

993
01:21:29,000 --> 01:21:33,073
The one constant through all the years,
Ray, has been baseball.

994
01:21:33,920 --> 01:21:37,117
America has rolled by
like an army of steamrollers.

995
01:21:37,600 --> 01:21:41,275
It's been erased like a blackboard,
rebuilt, and erased again.

996
01:21:43,000 --> 01:21:45,719
But baseball has marked the time.

997
01:21:47,480 --> 01:21:49,948
This field, this game.

998
01:21:50,800 --> 01:21:52,995
It's a part of our past, Ray.

999
01:21:53,680 --> 01:21:56,717
It reminds us of all that once was good...

1000
01:21:57,960 --> 01:21:59,951
...and it could be again.

1001
01:22:02,960 --> 01:22:04,837
People will come, Ray.

1002
01:22:05,720 --> 01:22:07,790
People will most definitely come.

1003
01:22:08,840 --> 01:22:11,638
Ray, you will lose everything.

1004
01:22:12,280 --> 01:22:14,316
You will be evicted.

1005
01:22:24,760 --> 01:22:26,193
<i>Come on, Ray.</i>

1006
01:22:46,320 --> 01:22:47,389
I'm not signing.

1007
01:22:48,040 --> 01:22:50,076
You're crazy! Absolutely nuts!

1008
01:22:50,800 --> 01:22:52,518
I can't do it, pal.

1009
01:22:54,040 --> 01:22:56,918
Ray, you build a baseball field
in the middle of nowhere...

1010
01:22:57,000 --> 01:22:58,752
...and you stare at nothing.

1011
01:22:58,840 --> 01:22:59,875
It's not nothing.

1012
01:22:59,960 --> 01:23:03,669
- Your daughter's turned into a space case.
- Get your hands off her!

1013
01:23:05,480 --> 01:23:06,629
Karin?

1014
01:23:11,360 --> 01:23:13,032
- Is she all right?
- I don't know.

1015
01:23:13,120 --> 01:23:15,554
- Is she breathing?
- Should I get the car?

1016
01:23:20,560 --> 01:23:22,516
I'm going to call emergency.

1017
01:23:23,840 --> 01:23:26,195
- Annie, wait.
- What?

1018
01:23:43,480 --> 01:23:44,754
Just wait.

1019
01:24:02,440 --> 01:24:04,954
- What have we got here?
- She fell.

1020
01:24:12,600 --> 01:24:15,433
- This child's choking to death.
- Get her up.

1021
01:24:15,880 --> 01:24:17,472
Hold her steady now.

1022
01:24:23,400 --> 01:24:25,470
Hot dog. Stuck in her throat.

1023
01:24:26,520 --> 01:24:28,112
She'll be all right.

1024
01:24:28,200 --> 01:24:31,351
She'll be turning handsprings
before you know it.

1025
01:24:35,000 --> 01:24:36,353
Thank you, Doc.

1026
01:24:37,920 --> 01:24:40,480
No, son. Thank you.

1027
01:24:43,760 --> 01:24:45,796
Oh, my God. You can't go back.

1028
01:24:46,080 --> 01:24:47,718
- You can't go back.
- It's all right.

1029
01:24:47,800 --> 01:24:49,791
- I'm sorry.
- It's all right.

1030
01:24:54,400 --> 01:24:56,356
I best be getting on home...

1031
01:24:56,840 --> 01:25:00,071
...before Alicia begins to think
I got a girlfriend.

1032
01:25:04,960 --> 01:25:06,234
Hey, Doc.

1033
01:25:06,840 --> 01:25:08,353
Good work, Doc.

1034
01:25:10,200 --> 01:25:11,713
Nice going, Doc.

1035
01:25:14,720 --> 01:25:16,039
Going to miss you.

1036
01:25:18,480 --> 01:25:21,074
Win one for me one day, will you, boys?

1037
01:25:21,160 --> 01:25:22,752
- Okay, Doc.
- Yeah.

1038
01:25:30,320 --> 01:25:32,834
When did these ballplayers get here?

1039
01:25:38,120 --> 01:25:39,519
Hey, rookie!

1040
01:25:50,800 --> 01:25:52,279
You were good.

1041
01:26:05,760 --> 01:26:09,435
Do not sell this farm, Ray.
You got to keep this farm.

1042
01:26:09,760 --> 01:26:11,876
You've had a rough day.

1043
01:26:11,960 --> 01:26:14,997
- Go inside and get something cold to drink.
- Yeah.

1044
01:26:15,080 --> 01:26:16,593
That's a good idea.

1045
01:26:17,840 --> 01:26:19,637
Don't sell the farm, Ray.

1046
01:26:28,400 --> 01:26:29,469
Ray?

1047
01:26:30,520 --> 01:26:32,431
We're going to call it a day.

1048
01:26:32,760 --> 01:26:35,035
- See you tomorrow.
- Okay.

1049
01:26:39,440 --> 01:26:41,158
Do you want to come with us?

1050
01:26:45,480 --> 01:26:47,869
- You mean it?
- No, not you.

1051
01:26:49,520 --> 01:26:50,555
Him.

1052
01:26:54,000 --> 01:26:55,831
- Him?
- Come with you?

1053
01:26:56,040 --> 01:26:57,712
- Out there.
- What is out there?

1054
01:26:58,400 --> 01:26:59,515
Come and find out.

1055
01:26:59,680 --> 01:27:02,148
Wait a second. Why him? I built this field.

1056
01:27:02,240 --> 01:27:06,028
- You wouldn't be here if it weren't for me.
- I'm unattached. You have a family.

1057
01:27:06,120 --> 01:27:07,678
I want to know what's out there.

1058
01:27:07,760 --> 01:27:10,274
- I want to see it.
- But you're not invited.

1059
01:27:13,000 --> 01:27:15,912
"Not invited"?
What do you mean I'm not invited?

1060
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:18,719
That's my corn out there.
You guys are guests in my corn.

1061
01:27:19,240 --> 01:27:23,313
I've done everything I've been asked to do.
I didn't understand, but I've done it.

1062
01:27:23,400 --> 01:27:25,516
I haven't once asked what's in it for me.

1063
01:27:25,600 --> 01:27:29,229
- What are you saying?
- I'm saying, "What's in it for me?"

1064
01:27:30,080 --> 01:27:32,833
Is that why you did this? For you?

1065
01:27:38,280 --> 01:27:40,794
I think you'd better stay here, Ray.

1066
01:27:43,880 --> 01:27:44,869
Why?

1067
01:27:46,720 --> 01:27:49,518
Ray. There's a reason they chose me...

1068
01:27:49,600 --> 01:27:52,273
...just as there's a reason
they chose you and this field.

1069
01:27:53,640 --> 01:27:54,993
I gave an interview.

1070
01:27:55,200 --> 01:27:57,191
What are you talking about?

1071
01:27:57,280 --> 01:28:01,398
The one about Ebbets Field,
the one that sent you to Boston to find me.

1072
01:28:04,280 --> 01:28:07,716
- You lied to me.
- You were kidnapping me at the time.

1073
01:28:07,800 --> 01:28:10,473
- You lied to me!
- You said your finger was a gun.

1074
01:28:13,040 --> 01:28:15,076
- That's a good point.
- Ray.

1075
01:28:20,440 --> 01:28:22,670
Listen to me, Ray. Listen to me.

1076
01:28:24,480 --> 01:28:26,630
There is something out there...

1077
01:28:27,160 --> 01:28:29,958
...and if I have the courage
to go through with this...

1078
01:28:30,040 --> 01:28:32,076
...what a story it'll make.

1079
01:28:33,800 --> 01:28:36,758
"Shoeless Joe Jackson comes to Iowa."

1080
01:28:45,120 --> 01:28:48,669
- Are you going to write about it?
- You bet I'll write about it.

1081
01:28:49,000 --> 01:28:52,709
- You're going to write about it.
- That's what I do.

1082
01:28:57,000 --> 01:28:58,115
Good.

1083
01:29:01,440 --> 01:29:02,555
Good.

1084
01:29:17,560 --> 01:29:19,551
Honey, where's he going?

1085
01:29:20,080 --> 01:29:22,753
Terry's been invited
to go out with the other players.

1086
01:29:22,840 --> 01:29:25,593
- How are you feeling, sweetheart?
- Stupid.

1087
01:29:25,760 --> 01:29:27,034
You mean "out"?

1088
01:29:27,280 --> 01:29:28,395
Yeah.

1089
01:29:29,360 --> 01:29:30,429
Out.

1090
01:29:31,040 --> 01:29:32,268
Far out.

1091
01:29:34,360 --> 01:29:35,952
I want a full description.

1092
01:29:36,880 --> 01:29:38,916
Take care of this family.

1093
01:29:41,240 --> 01:29:42,673
Be careful.

1094
01:30:39,280 --> 01:30:40,349
'Bye.

1095
01:30:43,440 --> 01:30:44,555
What?

1096
01:30:51,360 --> 01:30:53,430
What are you grinning at, you ghost?

1097
01:30:54,320 --> 01:30:56,276
"If you build it...

1098
01:30:58,160 --> 01:30:59,593
"...he will come."

1099
01:31:11,360 --> 01:31:14,477
- Oh, my God.
- What? What is it?

1100
01:31:18,440 --> 01:31:19,634
It's my father.

1101
01:31:25,040 --> 01:31:26,632
"Ease his pain."

1102
01:31:27,960 --> 01:31:29,871
"Go the distance."

1103
01:31:32,480 --> 01:31:33,913
It was you.

1104
01:31:37,640 --> 01:31:40,518
No, Ray. It was you.

1105
01:32:06,120 --> 01:32:07,473
My God.

1106
01:32:08,720 --> 01:32:12,156
I only saw him years later
when he was worn down by life.

1107
01:32:14,120 --> 01:32:15,155
Look at him.

1108
01:32:17,000 --> 01:32:21,676
He's got his whole life in front of him,
and I'm not even a glint in his eye.

1109
01:32:26,320 --> 01:32:28,117
What do I say to him?

1110
01:32:29,800 --> 01:32:32,837
Why don't you introduce him
to his granddaughter?

1111
01:32:35,880 --> 01:32:36,869
Hi.

1112
01:32:38,120 --> 01:32:39,109
Hi.

1113
01:32:39,680 --> 01:32:42,797
I just wanted to thank you folks
for putting up this field...

1114
01:32:42,880 --> 01:32:44,711
...letting us play here.

1115
01:32:45,240 --> 01:32:46,798
I'm John Kinsella.

1116
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:50,194
I'm Ray.

1117
01:32:51,680 --> 01:32:53,159
My wife Annie.

1118
01:32:54,200 --> 01:32:57,351
This is my daughter Karin.
Karin, this is my...

1119
01:33:00,600 --> 01:33:02,033
This is John.

1120
01:33:03,040 --> 01:33:04,155
Hi, John.

1121
01:33:06,520 --> 01:33:07,953
Hi, Karin.

1122
01:33:10,480 --> 01:33:13,233
Well, we're going to let you two talk.

1123
01:33:14,480 --> 01:33:18,598
If all these people are going to come,
we got a lot of work to do.

1124
01:33:20,600 --> 01:33:22,795
It was very nice meeting you.

1125
01:33:23,760 --> 01:33:24,795
Ma'am.

1126
01:33:26,120 --> 01:33:27,553
Come on.

1127
01:33:41,800 --> 01:33:43,677
You catch a good game.

1128
01:33:44,760 --> 01:33:46,034
Thank you.

1129
01:33:48,280 --> 01:33:50,032
It's so beautiful here.

1130
01:33:52,200 --> 01:33:53,315
For me...

1131
01:33:55,560 --> 01:33:58,358
For me, it's like a dream come true.

1132
01:34:01,720 --> 01:34:03,631
Can I ask you something?

1133
01:34:07,240 --> 01:34:09,276
Is this heaven?

1134
01:34:13,360 --> 01:34:14,634
It's Iowa.

1135
01:34:16,600 --> 01:34:19,068
- Iowa?
- Yeah.

1136
01:34:22,760 --> 01:34:25,069
I could have sworn it was heaven.

1137
01:34:33,000 --> 01:34:36,197
Is there a heaven?

1138
01:34:38,280 --> 01:34:39,554
Oh, yeah.

1139
01:34:41,720 --> 01:34:44,109
It's the place where dreams come true.

1140
01:35:03,120 --> 01:35:04,951
Maybe this is heaven.

1141
01:35:11,280 --> 01:35:12,759
Good night, Ray.

1142
01:35:15,520 --> 01:35:16,953
Good night, John.

1143
01:35:26,800 --> 01:35:28,438
Hey! Dad?

1144
01:35:32,240 --> 01:35:34,151
You want to have a catch?

1145
01:35:36,720 --> 01:35:38,153
I'd like that.

1146
01:37:16,960 --> 01:37:18,951
Subtitles by SOFTITLER


